==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lout
<hw>Lout</hw> <pr>(lout)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>louten</ets>, <ets>luten</ets>, AS. <ets>l⟦umac⟧tan</ets>; akin to
Icel. <ets>l⟦umac⟧ta</ets>, Dan. <ets>lude</ets>, OHG.
<ets>l⟦umac⟧z⟦emac⟧n</ets> to lie hid.]</ety> <def>To bend; to box; to
stoop.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au>
<au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He fair the knight saluted, <qex>louting</qex> low.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lout
<hw>Lout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Formerly also written
<ets>lowt</ets>.]</ety> <def>A clownish, awkward fellow; a
bumpkin.</def> <rj><au>Sir P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Lout
<hw>Lout</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To treat as a lout or fool; to
neglect; to disappoint.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loutish</ent>⟦br⟧
